\title{Quadratic Modeling for 3-SAT Problem}
\author{Fateme Abdi}
\maketitle

We assume that our function f(x) is a product of n sets, each set being the sum of 3 elements of our primary set:
\begin{equation}
f(x) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} s_i
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
s_i = \sum_{j=1}^{3} a_j.
\end{equation}

For our model, we declare a variable $ x_i $. If $ x_i = 0 $, it means we are using the variable $ a_i $ itself; but if $ x_i = 1 $, it means we are using the variable $ \overline{a_i} $.
we assume the number of $x_i$s to be m.

There is another variable we might want to declare as $ y_{i,j} $, where $ y_{i,j} = 1 $ if variable $ a_i $ or $ \overline{a_i} $ exists in the j-th term; logically, if it does not, $ y_{i,j} = 0 $.

Also, the main variable taking random values due to quantum operations is $ z_{i,j} $. We have $ 3n $ of them taking values according to the Ising model: $ 1 $ if $ a_i $ or $ \overline{a_i} $ is  1  in the j-th term, and  -1  if it is  0 .

So for every term, we have three combinations:
\begin{align}
-1, -1, -1 & \equiv 0, 0, 0 \\
-1, 1, -1 & \equiv 0, 1, 0 \\
1, -1, 1 & \equiv 1, 0, 1 \\
1, 1, 1 & \equiv 1, 1, 1.
\end{align}

The first function we are trying to build is to charge the total cost if any term has its three variables taking boolean value  0 :
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( \left( \sum_{j=1}^{3} z_{i,j} \right)^2 - 3 \left\lfloor \frac{\sum_{j=1}^{3} z_{i,j}}{3} \right\rfloor \right).
\end{equation}
the second part of our function checks whether our $x_i$ takes the same value in every term or not. if not costs more.
\begin{equation}
-\sum_{k=1}^{m}(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sum_{j=1}^{n}((y_{k,j}-2*x_k)*z_{i,j}))^2
\end{equation}
the overall equation is:
\begin{equation}
A\sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( \left( \sum_{j=1}^{3} z_{i,j} \right)^2 - 3 \left\lfloor \frac{\sum_{j=1}^{3} z_{i,j}}{3} \right\rfloor \right) - B\sum_{k=1}^{m} \left( \sum_{i=1}^{k} \sum_{j=1}^{n} (y_{k,j} - 2x_k) z_{i,j} \right)^2 
\end{equation}


